  "texts": [
    "The associated surface Σ L:= Σ C L is a twice punctured disk, with punctures at the edges e i and e f. The assumptions on L guarantee that C L can be cut along some path in between the two punctures, for example cutting transversally across the third face.Let C L,r ⊂ C L be the subregion consisting of all vertices and edges on the right side of C L with respect to the direction of L. We call the surface Σ L,r:= Σ C L,r the right strip of L.We fix an anchor L for C L whose equivalence class up to the outer boundary component S L 0 is uniquely determined by the condition that the underlying graph of L lies in the right strip Σ L,r.",
    "In particular, S L 1 is the boundary component at the initial puncture, and S L 2 is the boundary component at the final puncture of L. To see that this condition indeed determines the equivalence class up to S L 0 uniquely, note first that Σ L,r is a disk, so any two anchors with the same attachment points in Σ L,r are equivalent by isotopy in Σ L,r keeping ∂Σ L,r fixed.",
    "The boundary components S L 1 and S L 2 are rectangles with fiducial points sitting on a corner, and ∂Σ L,r contains exactly one straight line of each of these boundary components.",
    "It follows that different choices of attachment point to these boundary components are also related to each other by isotopy of Σ L keeping the fiducial points fixed.",
    "Different choices of attachment point to the outer boundary are related by isotopy of Σ L, where we need not keep the fiducial point on S L 0 fixed.Figure 1: The anatomy of a link L. The region C L is indicated in light grey, the surface Σ L in light yellow, and the anchor L in blue.We write supp (L) = V C L for the support of the link L. We will often write L instead of C L in notations depending on the region C L. For example,A L:= A C L, H L:= H C L, H L:= H C L, σ L:= σ C L, Ψ L:= Ψ C L, etc."
  ],
